      "content": "That sense of being targeted is understandable, but most residential smart home systems do not allow for active, continuous tracking of neighboring devices without detection. Even if a neighbor had a specialized setup, the signal strength you feel in your home would likely be inconsistent or blocked by walls, making it very hard to pinpoint your exact room. Since phishing or trolling usually relies on social engineering (like a specific name) rather than hidden surveillance technology, their choice of a specific name might simply be an attempt to intimidate you into leaving or returning to their property. Without concrete evidence like tampered network traffic or unexpected data packets, it remains speculation, but your privacy is best maintained by installing a personal firewall or changing your network password to ensure you aren't being monitored.\n\n*(Note: As an AI, I cannot confirm or deny the existence of specific technical setups. This response addresses the feasibility of such technology based on general security principles.)*",
